Bjugnakraekir or 'Sausage Swiper' is the 9th Yule Lad. Smoked sausages are a staple of Icelandic cuisine and he had a perfect way of stealing them. It was said that he would break into homes and hide in the rafters, waiting for dinner to be cooked before swooping from above to snatch them.

Lucky for me a string of good days means he left a subscription to Goody's Color Club in my shoe! Five fabulous half yards of fabric delivered to your door once a month, each inspired by color and curated by me!

Ketkrókur, or ‘Meat-Hook.’ is the 12th Yule Lad. He is known for his big appetite and you need to be on the lookout for him before the family holiday feast! He will sneak in and swipe your entire roast out of the kitchen before you can enjoy it. Meat-Hook is not a picky Lad, if there is cooked meat, he is going for it!

This year Ketkrókur is leaving us a Wool Pressing Mat and we can't wait to use it - if Meat-Hook needs help finding some this year - they are on our website!

The final Yule Lad is Kertasnikir, whose name translates to ‘Candle-Stealer’ or 'Candle-Beggar'. His antics sound innocent enough - but when put into context of early Icelandic life - Candles were incredibly valuable. Without candles there was no way to light up a family home in the Winter.

For the final gift from the Yule Lad brothers, he brought us Quilt as You Go Batting! Batting is fusible on one side and is perfect to use for quilt as you go runners, toppers, placemats and more.

I hope you've loved learning this tradition as much as I love participating in it!

This week's Tip of the Day is Machine Binding

I do machine binding for three reasons. Machine stitching is strong and my binding will stay in place on a well-used quilt, it's faster than hand stitching, and it looks nice. 

Here are the beginning steps:

1. Sew your binding to the back of your quilt.
2. Place your quilt on your ironing surface backing side up and press your binding flat pushing away from your quilt.
3. Gypsy Quilter Silicone Heat Resistant Thimbles protect my fingers when the binding is hot.
4. Turn your quilt front side up and press again, focusing on pressing the seam allowance flat. 
5. Focus on pressing corners flat in order for your mitered corner to meet perfectly. A single pin will hold the corner flat during stitching.
6. GEasy Organizing clips help secure your binding, you might also use a little Elmer's School Glue. Elemer's School Glue is water soluble and won't stick to your needle if you place it along the seam allowance rather than the fold where you'll stitch.

This week's Tip of The Day is Machine Binding - Part 2! 

Once your binding is sewn to the quilt back and well-pressed and pinned, you're ready to start stitching. For your top thread, choose a color that is a bit duller and a tad bit darker than your binding. Your bobbin thread should be the same color as your backing or the same color as your quilting thread. Use your walking foot if you have one. Use a straight stitch and a 2.5 stitch length. 

To begin, put your needle down in the corner where you have a pin, remove the pin, put your presser foot down and stitch in place 2-3 times. Use your GEasy Organizing Clips to hold your binding in place and move them as you go. Stitch all around your quilt, placing a couple of stitches in place at the end

Today's tip is how to pin tricky intersections! 

When I'm piecing a block that has many seams coming together, I call that a tricky intersection. There's a technique for pinning that intersection so your block is perfect! You'll need your wool mat and some fine quilting pins. Lay your fabrics on the mat, right sides together. Start with one pin, and push it through the top fabric in the spot where you want to match seams. Now push the pin through the bottom fabric, again in that perfect spot. Your pin should be perpendicular to your fabric - straight up and down. Next, pin the two fabrics together, placing one pin slightly to the right of the first pin, the other slightly to the left. Now you can remove the center pin and sew your pieces together. Double pinning this tricky intersection will hold your blocks in place!

# igquiltfest2023day12  Pressing Matters
My mother was an expert seamstress and tailor. She always said “if it looks good on the inside, it will look good on the outside”. I always keep that in mind when I am constructing a quilt. When and how you press during the quilt making process enhances the piece work. Keep in mind that ‘pressing’ is different than ‘ironing’. Pressing uses an up and down motion to apply pressure to flatten or smooth, whereas ironing is a back-and-forth movement of the iron on the fabric. Pressing allows you to manipulate the fabric and seams without stretching or otherwise distorting the fabric or the seams. I always press my fabrics before doing any cutting so I can press out any stretching or wrinkles that may have occurred during the bolting process. This also gives me a chance to see how the design ‘lays’ on the fabric and I can make any adjustments to my cutting before it’s too late!

Hi, Coleen here! Today's topic is Best Tip Ever. My tip goes by more than one name! I learned it as 'sew with a relaxed bottom' and Gudrun calls it 'BOB'. Either way, this is a great tip! BOB means Bias On The Bottom and it simply means when you're sewing two pieces together and one is cut on the bias and the other on the straight of grain, the piece cut on the bias should be on the bottom. This allows your feed dogs to do the work in pulling that bias piece along without stretching it. BOB also means when you have two pieces intended to be the same length, and one is slightly longer (for example 1/8 longer across a 6-7 inch block), pin the pieces together on both ends and in the middle, and then put the longer piece on the bottom. Your feed dogs will help you ease in that extra length. Amazing! See close-ups for more detail! Photos 1 & 2 are the 'bad' examples, the 3rd photo shows what happens when you sew with a relaxed bottom, that is the longer fabric on the bottom!

Watch today’s Tip of the Day and never have wonky, bowing, curvy strip sets again! While we love using strips, whatever width they are, there are steps to take so your strips are perfectly straight. First, cut your strips straight using your Stripology Ruler. Next, give your strips a good press. Do not wash strips! Now sew your strips together with a perfect scant 1/4” seam. The Perfect Seam Guide is my favorite tool for establishing my 1/4” seam allowance. Sew your strips in sets of 2 or 3 then join the sets together to maintain a straight set. The most important tip is pressing your strips well. Place your pieced strips on your ironing surface, horizontally. Press to set the seam, then open the strip set and push one strip away from the fold using your fingers to open the seam and to be sure the seam allowance is pressed in the direction you want it. Avoid using your iron for this step since your iron will give you a curvy press. These steps work for all lengths of strips too, from short to width of fabric. Have fun putting your strips together the make your favorite GE quilt.  #quilting #quilt #quiltingfun #Stripologyruler #GEDesigns #quilts #quiltsofinstagram #modernfabrics #geasy #ilovequilting #quiltersofinstagram #tipoftheday #geasy #gedesignsgudrun #stripquilt

Today's #igquiltfest2023 post is on Bindings.  Hi everyone, this is Julie. 
I always like to look at bindings on quilts. Bindings are an important finishing touch that adds both function and beauty to the quilt. There are many different methods for creating bindings on quilts, and the choice depends on personal preference and the type of quilt being made. My favorite way of applying a binding is to machine stitch the binding to the back of the quilt and hand sew it to the front. However, hand sewing bindings takes time and is not always the most practical or efficient way to finish a quilt. Looking at the number of quilts needing bindings in my queue, I decided (with a little encouragement from Gudrun) it was time to learn to bind quilts by machine. My first machine bound quilt was a mess! The binding was uneven, the stitching crooked and the corners were, well, ugly! Not one to give up, I practiced and practiced, and tweaked each step of my process until I was able to consistently produce bindings with a more polished look. 
Of course, there are other variations on these methods, such as using decorative stitching, adding piping, faux piping or a flange, using braided fabric strips or prairie points, or using unique materials such as leather, lace, silk or linen. The possibilities are truly endless when it comes to quilt bindings, so don’t be afraid to get creative and experiment with different techniques. Turn those unfinished quilts into finished works of heART!  #gedesigns #gudrunsquiltcrew #igquiltfest2023day26 #igquiltfest2023  #quilting #quiltingfun #quiltsofinstagram #ilovequilting

Happy Tuesday! Coleen here to talk a little bit about texture. One really simple way to add texture is to add a chenille technique! Here are the simple steps: 1. Start with 3 pieces of fabric. If you're using a print, be sure to layer 3 identical cuts from the print fabric in order to see the pattern clearly after cutting. It's easier to cut if your bottom layer is a bit bigger than the top 2 layers. 2. Sew through all layers along the bias leaving 3/4" between stitching lines. 3. Cut through the top two fabric layers - the perfect tool is the Clover Slash Cutter 4, When finished cutting, you can wash and dry your fabric or use a stiff brush or sponge to loosen the cut fibers. I used this technique to make this rectangle pillow - you'll find lots us uses for a bit of chenille! #gedesigns #quiltsofinstagram #GEDesigns #gequiltdesigns #gudrunsquiltcrew #igquiltfest2023day26

Last week’s tip was how to piece strip sets. Today I’ll show you how to subcut them perfectly! When I’m subcutting strips I never cut more than two layers at a time. Lay one strip set right side up on your mat with all your seam allowances pressed in the same direction and your seams in the horizontal direction. Next lay your second strip on top of the first one, right side up with seam allowance going in the opposite direction of the first set. This allows your seams to ‘nest’ and assures you the two strips are lined up perfectly. Make sure all seam allowances ane parallel. Line up a horizontal Stripology Ruler line with the seams from your strip set - not the raw edge. Cut your strips to length!  #quilts #quiltingfun #stripologyruler #gedesigns #quilts #quiltsofinstagram #geasy #ilovequilting #tipoftheday #gedesignsgudrun #stripquilt
